[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+       48[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+       49[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mThe problem:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;192;197;206m The drafts table stores [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mprovider_id[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m on each record, and the "Why These Services" section notes that the access pattern is "lookup by message ID or by provider ID for their review queue." But the recipe never addresses how the Provider Inbox UI enforces that Dr. Martinez sees only drafts for their own patients (or for the care team they're covering), and not drafts belonging to Dr. Patel. This is a classic multi-tenant PHI access control problem.[K
[0m[48;2;43;48;59m[39m   32,  50[0m:[39m[48;2;43;48;59m [K
[0m[48;2;79;40;40m[39m-  33     [0m:[39m[48;2;36;25;28m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mLocation:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;192;197;206m Step 3 (Assemble the prompt), and the general architecture discussion.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+       51[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mA naive implementation that queries the drafts table by [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mprovider_id[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m from URL parameters (rather than from an authenticated session principal) is trivially exploitable. A slightly less naive one that uses session principal still needs to handle cross-coverage scenarios (Dr. Martinez is covering for Dr. Patel this weekend). Neither is addressed.[K
